I think a lot about millennials who were the last generation able to connect with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during an age of media gold, with a collective consciousness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We dove directly into things without worrying about the source, because it wasn't so easy to determine.
Without reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships became foundations for our lives.
This is why we are so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the show every Thursday.
This doesn't resemble what we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and where each person watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specific closed spaces.
Unconsciously, we die to be part of the universal community that surrounded all of this.
This is why so many people watch series like The Office or movies like The Producers obsessively, with lots of short references, just like memes.
We repeated these refs, knowing that most people knew them.
now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
there are too many things to see and no way to rationalize it all... will we escape hyper-saturation?
we get caught in cycles of discovering new media, only to realize that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
we are forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while recognizing that the people who created the art we connect with can be very imperfect.
we engage in parasocial relationships more mindfully.
We understand it's hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without crushing others along the way.
In the absence of collective media consciousness, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us remain critical.
Some of us continue to place people on pedestals, only to be shocked when they fall.
We are in a tumultuous period and I can't wait to see where it will lead us.
